tab within one of your clusters.

: Choose from a set of pre-defined time periods relative to your current time. Using relative time ranges allows you to check metrics in a periodical and convenient way, without needing to enter the specific start and end time. Your choices include:
: Enter the exact start time and end time. Using absolute range allows you to control the metrics you see in a more fine-tuned way.
The time difference between the start and the end time should be greater than 10 minutes.
Zilliz Cloud offers metric charts for monitoring cluster performance from various aspects.  For a quick overview of available metrics, refer to
To effectively track pod resource consumption, select the
area. Here, you'll find succinct graphs that display CPU, storage, and network usage for each pod.
: Review a pod's CPU activity, noting the usage, node capacity, and defined resource requests and limits.
: Check the storage consumption for each pod.
: Examine a pod's data transfer rates, both incoming and outgoing.
Use the dropdown on the right to filter the display for particular components like Proxy, QueryNode, Coordinator, or DataNode.
To view metric charts for resource usage, select the
area. These charts provide a snapshot of the cluster's resource usage, including computation, capacity, and storage.
: Measures computational power usage relative to the total.
: Indicates used capacity as a percentage of total, measured per second over time.
100%: When the used CU capacity hits 100%, Zilliz Cloud disables data writing and triggers SDK errors. To restore normal functionality,
: Shows total persistent storage consumed, calculated in GB/s over a selected period.
To view metric charts for performance, select the
area. These charts provide a snapshot of cluster performance, including
: The number of read requests (search and query) per second.
: The number of read requests (search) on vectors per second. VPS is not available for query requests as query operations do not involve vectors.
: The number of write requests (insert, bulk insert, upset, and delete) per second.
: The number of write requests (insert, bulk insert,upset, and delete) on vectors per second.
: The time elapsed between a client sending a read request (search and query request) to a server and the client receiving a response. It includes an average latency and a P99 latency.
: The time elapsed between a client sending a write request (insert and upsert request) to a server and the client receiving a response. It includes an average latency and a P99 latency.
: The percentage of timeout read requests in all requests per second.
: The percentage of timeout write requests in all requests per second.
To view metric charts for business data, select the
area. These charts provide a snapshot of the cluster's entity data by indicating the number of collections, entities, and loaded entities in the cluster.
: The count of collections created in the cluster.
: The count of entities inserted into the cluster.
: The count of entities loaded in the cluster.
: The number of connections to the current cluster. This metric type is available only for
